Drain and rinse the @red kidney beans{1%pack} in a #sieve{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Halve the @chilli{1}(finely chopped) and discard the core and seeds.

Halve the @bell pepper{1}(sliced into thin strips) and discard the core and seeds.

Place a large #pot over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot fry the onion, garlic and pepper until softened, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Lower the heat to medium-high then add the @Mexican style spice mix{2%sachets} and fry for ~{1%minute}.

Add the beans, @vegetable stock powder{1%sachet}, @chopped tomatoes{1%pack} and chilli (use less if you don't like spice) to the pot.

> You can adjust the chilli quantity depending on your preferred spice level.

Cover and simmer for ~{8-10%minutes}.

Stir every so often to prevent sticking.

Meanwhile, quarter the @cauliflower{1} then coarsely grate with a #grater{} (if you have a #food processor{} you can use this instead).

Add a drizzle of oil and a knob of @butter{to taste} to a medium pan over medium-high heat.

When hot, cook the cauliflower rice until slightly softened, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring regularly.

Remove from the heat and season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Stir half the @creme fraiche{125%g} into the chilli and allow to warm through.

Add a splash of @water{to taste} if a looser consistency is desired.

Season to taste with salt, pepper and @sugar{to taste}.

> You can adjust the seasoning levels according to your taste.

Pick the @coriander leaves{5%g} (discard the stalks).

Divide the kidney bean chilli between #bowls{}.

Top with the remaining creme fraiche and coriander leaves.

Serve the cauliflower rice alongside.